under the inï¬‚uence of an external electric ï¬eld. We can imagine that these dipoles in the applied electric ï¬eld can have excess negative charges on one surface and positive charges on the opposite surface as shown in Figure 1.10.
These charges are not free, but each is bound to a molecule lying on or near the surface. The net charge per unit volume within the rest of the dielectric medium is zero. The electric ï¬eld E1 set up by the induced charge always opposes the applied ï¬eld E0. The resultant ï¬eld E is the vector sum of these two. That is,

E = E0 + E1

(1.6)

The ï¬eld E1 is called the depolarization ï¬eld, for within the body, it tends to oppose the applied ï¬eld E0 as shown in Figure 1.10. The resultant ï¬eld E points to the same direction as E0 but is smaller in magnitude. This leads to the conclusion that if a dielectric is placed in an electric ï¬eld, the induced surface charges

appear, which tend to weaken the original ï¬eld within the dielectric. Thus we can

deï¬ne the relative dielectric constant or relative permittivity ğœ€ as the ratio of the

magnitude of the applied ï¬eld E0 to the resultant ï¬eld E. Then,

