each cycle and to reduce the valve leakage problem, peristaltic micropump was designed [34]. In 1993, Stemme and Stemme ï¬rst proposed the valveless piezoelectric micropump [35].
The micropump basically includes two diï¬€user/nozzle elements, pump chamber, actuator unit, inlet and outlet channels, power supply module, and diaphragm/pump membrane as shown in Figure 3.13a,b. Actuator is necessary to operate the diaphragm of the micropump. The actuator is made up of a piezoelectric disk and a silicon membrane. The piezoelectric disk is made up of piezoelectric material such as PZT to yield mechanical strain by an external electric ï¬eld. The diï¬€user/nozzle determines the performance of the micropump. Diï¬€user with two ï¬‚at walls made up of silicon is selected for the proposed micropump design, which has a rectangular cross section with two parallel ï¬‚at walls and two convergent ï¬‚at walls as shown in Figure 3.14. The basic dimensions of the diï¬€user element involve the divergence angle ğœƒ, the diï¬€user length L, and the width of the narrowest part W 1 [37].

