One-inlet and one-outlet ï¬‚ow hole is drilled in the inlet/outlet cavity of the micropump. Two short brass pipes are ï¬xed to the pump inlet and outlet holes for the tube attachment. A pump chamber having circular cavity made up of silicon and covered by glass substrate is considered. The diaphragm closes the cavity of the pump chamber, and it is bonded with the center disk of the actuator. In reciprocating pumping method, the ï¬‚ow rate of the micropump depends on the stroke volume, which is the volume change in the chamber caused by diaphragm motion. A circular silicon diaphragm of 0.1 mm thickness and 6 mm in diameter is considered. An alternating voltage of 50 V (0 to peak) is applied across the piezoelectric disk. This voltage is required to be switched in the form of â€œonâ€ and â€œoï¬€â€ such that required frequency of this voltage can be applied to the PZT stack to achieve pumping action. As a result, a control unit is interfaced between the power supply module and the micropump.
The pump operation is based on the ï¬‚uid ï¬‚ow rectifying properties of the two nozzle/diï¬€user elements. The dimension diï¬€erence at both ends of the diï¬€user causes the pressure diï¬€erence and drives the ï¬‚uid. The pump cycle of the pump is divided into a â€œsupply modeâ€ and a â€œpump mode.â€ In the supply mode, the actuator increases the chamber volume, resulting in lower pressure inside the chamber. As a result, a larger amount of ï¬‚uid ï¬‚ows into the chamber through the input element, which acts as a diï¬€user, rather than through the input element, which acts as a nozzle. In the pump mode, the actuator decreases the chamber volume, resulting in higher pressure inside the chamber. As a result, a larger amount of ï¬‚uid ï¬‚ows out of the chamber through the output element, which acts as a diï¬€user, rather than through the output element, which acts as a nozzle [37].
Conventional drug delivery methods such as oral medications, inhalers, and subcutaneous injections do not deliver all drugs accurately and eï¬ƒciently within their desired therapeutic range. Generally most of the drugs are eï¬€ective if delivered within a speciï¬c range of concentration between the desired maximum and minimum levels. Above the maximum range, they are toxic, and below the minimum range, they have no therapeutic beneï¬t. With controlled drug delivery systems consisting of drug reservoir, micropumps, valves, microsensors, microchannels, and necessary related circuits, appropriate and eï¬€ective amount of drug can be precisely calculated by the controller and released at appropriate time by the microactuator mechanism such as micropump [38]. Micropumps are therefore an essential component in the ï¬‚uid transport systems.

