to produce more power for a given input acceleration [48]. Another less common material is aluminum nitride (AlN). Though it has a smaller piezoelectric coeï¬ƒcient and dielectric constant, aluminum nitride has advantages in material deposition and in compatibility with the standard CMOS processes used for fabrication of IC [49].
Piezoelectric materials have a built-in polarization and therefore respond differently to stresses depending on the direction. There are two primary modes of electromechanical coupling for piezoelectric materials: the 3â€“1 mode (d31) and the 3â€“3 mode (d33). In the 3â€“1 mode, the material has an induced electric ï¬eld in direction 3, as a response to the stress along direction 1, but in the 3â€“3 mode, the material is subjected to a stress in the same direction of the produced electric ï¬eld.
The vast majority of piezoelectric energy-harvesting devices use a cantilever beam structure. A cantilever beam, by deï¬nition, is a beam with a support only at one end and is often referred to as a ï¬xed-free beam. When the generator is subjected to vibrations in the vertical direction, the support structure will move up and down in sync with the external acceleration. The vibration of the beam is induced by its own inertia; since the beam is not perfectly rigid, it tends to deï¬‚ect when the base support moves up and down (Figure 3.21). Typically, a proof mass is added to the free end of the beam to increase that deï¬‚ection amount. This lowers the resonant frequency of the beam and increases the deï¬‚ection of the beam as it vibrates. The larger deï¬‚ection leads to more stress, more strain,

