In 2007, Henderson and Viggiano have designed the worldâ€™s smallest linear motor, at only 1.55 mm Ã— 1.55 mm square and 6 mm long [75, 76], as shown in Figure 3.31a. The actuator uses less than 0.1 W to produce 20 g of force at 5 mm sâˆ’1. Its high linear force, power, precision, and low cost make the motor ideal for numerous micro motion applications including mobile phone cameras, microï¬‚uidic devices, implantable drug pumps, and deformable mirrors for adaptive optics.
The piezoelectric linear SQUIGGLE motor uses ultrasonic standing-wave vibrations in a threaded nut to directly rotate a screw as shown in Figure 3.31b. This unique operating principle â€œwrapsâ€ the vibration motion of the nut around the screw threads to directly produce linear movement without requiring additional mechanical conversion. The thread friction is not parasitic but is used to directly rotate the screw. The threads multiply the linear force and position resolution and reduce the linear speed. The result is a tiny high-force motor capable of sub-micrometer stepping and velocity control without the need for a position sensor and high-speed servo control loop. Additional features include precise oï¬€-power hold and a manual adjustment option by turning the screw. The nut vibration is sometimes described as a â€œhula hoopâ€ or wobbling motion. A small axial preload maintains constant contact between the nut and screw threads, which causes the tangential friction force to rotate and translate the screw. Two orthogonal bending vibrations are combined to create the orbital motion. The two bending modes are created using orthogonal piezoelectric plates bonded to the outside of the metal nut.
In the SQUIGGLE motor, four PZT plates are bonded to ï¬‚at surfaces on the outside of the metal tube at 90âˆ˜ spacing. The poling directions are aligned such that a common drive voltage on opposite pairs of plates produces opposing strain. The opposing d31 strain is parallel to the plate surface and bends the nut. The bending strain is applied at a frequency matched to the ï¬rst bending resonant frequency of the tube (Figure 3.32). At this mechanical resonant frequency, a small PZT strain is ampliï¬ed by the Q of the mechanical system. By symmetry, the resonant frequency of the orthogonal PZT plate pairs is matched. The hula hoop vibration mode is created by generating PZT strain in orthogonal plate pairs at

