the titanium ion becomes an oï¬€-center position corresponding to a permanent electrical dipole.
As the temperature is changed, the crystallographic dimensions change due to distortion of the octahedra, resulting in octahedra being coupled together and having a very large spontaneous polarization that leads to a large dielectric constant. The spontaneous polarization is along one of the âŸ¨001âŸ© directions in the original cubic structure. Below 5 and âˆ’90 âˆ˜C, the orthorhombic phase is stable with the polarization along one of the âŸ¨110âŸ© directions in the original cubic structure. On decreasing the temperature below âˆ’90 âˆ˜C, the phase transition from the orthorhombic to rhombohedral phase leads to polarization along one of the âŸ¨111âŸ© cubic directions. These sensitive crystallographic ï¬‚uctuations with the temperature are shown in Figure 4.10.
BaTiO3 was the ï¬rst material used for manufacturing dielectric ceramics capacitors, MLCs, and so on. It is used for this application due to its high dielectric constant and low dielectric loss. The values of the dielectric constant depend on the synthesis route, which means purity, density, grain size, and so on [107]. The dielectric constant is also dependent on temperature, frequency, and dopants. Figure 4.11 shows the temperature dependence of the dielectric constant measured with a small ï¬eld along the pseudo-cubic edge [106, 108]. In this ï¬gure,

