To harvest energy using the piezoelectric virus-templated BTO, a well-established NG fabrication process is utilized, as illustrated by the schematics of Figure 4.16a. The stirred and inï¬ltrated virus-templated BTO nanostructures are mixed with PDMS to achieve the BTO piezoelectric layer (Figure 4.16a-i). The indium tin oxide (ITO)-coated thick (âˆ¼175 Î¼m) polyethylene terephthalate (PET) substrate is covered with PDMS dielectric layer to prevent the electric breakdown of device (Figure 4.16a-ii). The virus-templated BTO-based piezoelectric layer (âˆ¼200 Î¼m in thickness) was spin-casted on a PDMS-coated ï¬‚exible substrate. For the top electrode, an ITO-deposited thin PET substrate (âˆ¼50 Î¼m) is subsequently placed on the piezoelectric layer (Figure 4.16a-iii). Figure 4.16a-iv shows the photograph of fabricated virus-templated BTO NG that is malleable and ï¬‚exible. Due to the anisotropic structure of M13, the well-percolated nanoclusters of the virus-templated BTO were well distributed in a soft elastomeric matrix without any dispersion agents, as shown in the high-resolution SEM image of Figure 4.16a-v.
